# Portfolio Content Strategy Plan

> First-principles analysis of who visits your portfolio, when, and what they need to see.

---

## The Fundamental Insight

**Traditional portfolio thinking**: "Show my best work beautifully."

**First-principles portfolio thinking**: "Remove risk fast for each decision-maker at each stage."

Your portfolio isn't a museum. It's a risk-reduction machine. Each stage of the hiring funnel has someone asking: "Should I stake my reputation on recommending this person?"

**The risks they're evaluating**:
- **Capability risk**: Can you do this work?
- **Execution risk**: Will you actually ship?
- **Fit risk**: Do you think like us?
- **Trust risk**: Can I stake my reputation on you?

Every element of your portfolio should reduce one of these risks—instantly.

---

## Part 1: The Hiring Funnel Mapped

Based on your target company research, here's who touches your portfolio and when:

### Stage 1: Discovery (30 seconds)
**Who**: Recruiters (Anthropic, OpenAI, Block, Ramp) or Technical team (xAI has no recruiters)
**When**: First click from LinkedIn/application/referral
**Their question**: "Is this person worth 10 more minutes?"
**Time budget**: 30 seconds

> [!warning] xAI Exception
> xAI has no recruiters—technical team reviews everything from Stage 1. This means:
> - Technical depth must be discoverable within 1-2 clicks, not buried
> - The hero must satisfy BOTH recruiter-style scanning AND technical curiosity
> - Your GitHub link and code evidence should be visible on the home page, not just /lab
>
> **Design for xAI's path as a constraint that improves the whole portfolio.**

**What they scan for**:
- Years of experience (does title/intro signal seniority?)
- Domain relevance (AI? Fintech? Technical?)
- Portfolio exists and loads fast
- Social proof (companies worked with)
- **For xAI**: Technical credibility signals visible immediately (GitHub link, "ships code" chip)

**What they DON'T do**: Read case studies. Look at details. Scroll much (unless xAI—they might dig faster).

---

### Stage 2: Recruiter Deep-Dive (5-10 minutes)
**Who**: Internal recruiter or sourcer preparing to pass you forward
**When**: Before forwarding to design lead
**Their question**: "Can I confidently pitch this person to the hiring manager?"
**Time budget**: 5-10 minutes

**What they need**:
- Quick summary of 2-3 projects (not full case studies)
- Clear role/contribution on each project
- Signals of seniority (led team, owned product area, etc.)
- Enough to write an internal summary

**What they DON'T do**: Deep-dive into process. Care about code. Read long narratives.

---

### Stage 3: Design Lead Review (15-30 minutes)
**Who**: Head of Design, Design Manager, Principal Designer
**When**: Deciding whether to bring you to portfolio presentation
**Their question**: "Can this person think? Do they have taste? Will they raise the bar?"
**Time budget**: 15-30 minutes

**What they evaluate**:
- Design judgment (can they make hard calls?)
- Process clarity (do they know WHY they did things?)
- Visual craft (is the work beautiful?)
- Systems thinking (do they see the bigger picture?)
- Self-awareness (do they acknowledge constraints/tradeoffs?)

**Critical insight**: They're also evaluating if you can PRESENT. Your portfolio's structure foreshadows your portfolio presentation.

---

### Stage 4: Portfolio Presentation (30-60 minutes)
**Who**: 3-5 person panel (design leads, PM, eng, sometimes leadership)
**When**: The formal portfolio review round
**Their question**: "How does this person think through problems?"
**Time budget**: 30-60 minutes (you control the pace)

Company specifics from your research:
- **Anthropic**: 25 min presentation + 15-20 min Q&A
- **Block**: 45-60 min with 5-person panel, want PROCESS not outputs
- **Ramp**: 2 case studies, 30 min presentation + 30 min Q&A
- **xAI**: 45 min portfolio review, no recruiters means technical eye from start

**What differentiates**:
- Going deeper than surface level
- Handling tough questions gracefully
- Showing collaboration (how you worked with eng/PM)
- Demonstrating iteration (what you tried that didn't work)

---

### Stage 5: Technical Validation (varies)
**Who**: Engineering leads, technical interviewers
**When**: Technical rounds or async review
**Their question**: "Can this person actually ship? Or are they all pixels?"
**Time budget**: Targeted inspection

**What they look for**:
- GitHub profile (Anthropic explicitly mentions this)
- Code samples, prototypes
- Technical vocabulary in case studies
- Evidence of implementation knowledge

**Critical for you**: Anthropic's Claude Code role wants "CLI/terminal design experience" and "HTML/CSS/JS prototyping." This is explicit in their job descriptions.

---

### Stage 6: Post-Interview Reference (varies)
**Who**: Panel members after interviews, hiring committee
**When**: During debrief, decision-making
**Their question**: "What was that thing they mentioned about X?"
**Time budget**: Quick lookups

**What matters**: Your case studies need enough depth that someone can re-find specific details you discussed.

---

## Part 2: Target-Specific Signals

Use what you know from research to tune the story for each target:

### xAI
**Culture**: First-principles, proof-of-work, intensity, no BS
**What to signal**:
- Exceptional work right away, minimal fluff
- Tight logic, truth-seeking tone
- Evidence you can sustain intensity
- Technical depth visible immediately

**Positioning for xAI**: "First-principles product designer. I build AI systems that hold up under truth, finance, and real users."

### Anthropic
**Culture**: AI safety + reasoning + prototyping + code
**What to signal**:
- Claude Code usage prominently (you're applying to Claude Code role)
- AI agent work and prompt engineering
- Decision-making clarity
- Understanding of LLM capabilities/limitations
- GitHub profile, code samples

**Positioning for Anthropic**: "Designer who ships production code with Claude. Built AI agents. Understands the territory from the inside."

### OpenAI
**Culture**: Fast shipping, DERP pods, systems thinking
**What to signal**:
- Cross-functional pod-style work
- Speed and velocity
- Product thinking at scale
- Systems architecture

### Block
**Culture**: Fintech + mobile + measurable impact
**What to signal**:
- Fintech mastery (IFRS 2, vesting, compliance) — **this is your primary differentiator here, not AI**
- Mobile-first patterns
- Business metrics and outcomes
- Bitcoin/financial infrastructure thinking
- Leadership experience (they hire Principal level)

> [!note] Block Priority
> Block cares more about fintech depth + leadership than AI fluency. Don't over-index on Claude Code for Block—lead with "10+ years fintech systems, built design team, IFRS 2 expertise." AI is a bonus, not the headline.

### Ramp
**Culture**: PEDD (Product, Engineering, Design, Data), velocity, hybrid UX/UI
**What to signal**:
- Design-engineering fluency
- Data-informed decisions
- Shipped outcomes with metrics
- Business thinking in design challenge
- Fintech domain knowledge (expense management adjacent to your equity expertise)

> [!note] Ramp Priority
> Ramp's PEDD model values data as an equal partner. Your fintech expertise + ability to speak to metrics matters more than "I built an AI agent." Lead with "shipped products, data-informed decisions, enterprise scale."

