## Part 3: Content Strategy by Audience

### The Hero (Stage 1 Gate)

**Current PRD says**: "30-second test: Visitor immediately understands 'design engineer who ships with AI'"

**First-principles upgrade**: The hero shouldn't TELL them you're a design engineer who ships with AI. It should SHOW it.

**Non-generic approach**:

Instead of:
> "Hi, I'm Ion. I'm a design engineer who builds with AI."

Consider:
> A hero that IS the evidence—but with zero reliability risk.

> [!warning] Reliability First
> **Do NOT make the hero depend on live API calls.** A failed Claude API call or slow response at Stage 1 is worse than no demo. Recruiters on mobile are especially sensitive to load time. Any "live proof" element must:
> - Load instantly (cached/pre-rendered)
> - Degrade gracefully if API fails
> - Work fully offline if needed
>
> **Better approach**: Static hero with a CTA to the live agent page. The hero SHOWS the outcome (screenshot, animation), the /agent page PROVES you can build it.

**Specific elements for your hero**:
1. **Title line**: Direct, no fluff. "Lead Product Designer. Building with AI."
2. **Proof chips visible immediately** (not buried):
   - "10+ years" (experience signal)
   - Domain tags: "AI Products · Fintech Systems · Design Leadership" (NOT company names—avoids "you haven't worked there" bias)
   - "Ships production code" (technical signal)
3. **Visual hook**: A polished static visual (shipped product screenshot, system diagram) that loads instantly. NOT a live component.
4. **Social proof strip**: Ledgy logo + Sequoia badge + "4 founders vouching" or similar

> [!note] Balance AI vs. Fintech
> The hero must serve ALL targets. Over-indexing on "AI" risks being bucketed as "AI side project designer" for Block/Ramp, who care more about fintech depth and leadership. Lead with **"Principal Designer"** or **"Design Leader"**, mention AI as ONE of your domains, not THE identity.

**Anti-patterns to avoid**:
- Long paragraphs about yourself
- "I'm passionate about..."
- Photo taking up hero space
- Vague positioning statements
- Live API dependencies in hero
- Target company names as list (triggers "you haven't worked there" bias)

---

### Work Section (Stages 2-4)

**Current implementation**: Bottom floating dock + hero-first navigation. No sidebar.

**First-principles upgrade**: Results-first case studies with scrollytelling.

**The insight**: Showing outcomes first creates curiosity ("How did they achieve that?") rather than requiring commitment to read ("Let me tell you about a problem..."). This mirrors landing page logic: lead with value, then explain.

---

#### Work Index (`/work`)

```
/work index
├── Quick cards with: Title, 1-line outcome, key visual, impact metric, tags
├── Filterable by: Domain (AI, Fintech, Enterprise) and Type (Product, System, Prototype)
└── Sort by: Featured (default), Recent
```

Each card shows the RESULT, not the problem. Recruiters get talking points instantly.

---

#### Case Study Structure (`/work/[slug]`)

**Results-First Hero + 6-Section Scrollytelling**

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ RESULTS-FIRST HERO (above the fold) — THE HOOK                  │
│ ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── │
│ [Beautiful visual: shipped product, key UI, chart, or outcome]  │
│                                                                 │
│ PROJECT TITLE                                                   │
│ One-line outcome statement ("AI agent that transformed X")      │
│                                                                 │
│ ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐                         │
│ │ +40%     │ │ -35%     │ │ 10K      │  ← 3 Impact metrics     │
│ │ adoption │ │ time     │ │ users    │     (prominent, visual) │
│ └──────────┘ └──────────┘ └──────────┘                         │
│                                                                 │
│ Role: Lead Designer · Timeline: 6 months · Stack: React, Claude │
│                                                                 │
│ [Read the story ↓]                                              │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

SCROLLYTELLING SECTIONS (the story of how you got there)
├── 01 Problem    — Concise framing + user pain or business context
├── 02 Constraints — Tech, timeline, data, or compliance limits
├── 03 Approach   — Key decisions, tradeoffs, experiments
├── 04 System     — Architecture, flows, data model (+ collapsible deep-dives)
├── 05 Use Cases  — Interactive cards with filters (persona, platform)
└── 06 Results    — Expanded metrics, testimonials, learnings
```

---

#### Layout System: Sticky Rail + Scrollable Content

**Desktop (≥1024px)**:
- **Left sticky rail** ("Project Dossier"): Section number, title, 1-2 line summary. Also contains: project metadata, links (live/repo), outcome metrics, mini progress list.
- **Right scrollable column**: The actual story content with rich media, diagrams, interactive elements.

**Mobile**:
- Horizontal pill bar for section navigation (swipeable)
- Or: sections stack vertically with section headers acting as anchors
- Hero with metrics always visible first

**Scroll sync**:
- IntersectionObserver highlights active section on rail
- Updates left rail content as you scroll
- Triggers micro-animations on section entry

---

#### Section Data Model

```typescript
type CaseStudy = {
  // HERO (always visible above fold)
  hero: {
    title: string;
    tagline: string;           // "AI agent that transformed X"
    visual: MediaAsset;        // Key image, chart, or video
    metrics: Metric[];         // 3 impact numbers (prominent)
    role: string;
    timeline: string;
    stack: string[];
    links: { live?: string; repo?: string };
  };
  
  // SCROLLYTELLING SECTIONS (6 sections)
  sections: [
    { id: "01", title: "Problem",     type: "narrative" },
    { id: "02", title: "Constraints", type: "narrative" },
    { id: "03", title: "Approach",    type: "narrative" },
    { id: "04", title: "System",      type: "technical", hasCollapsibles: true },
    { id: "05", title: "Use Cases",   type: "interactive", filterable: true },
    { id: "06", title: "Results",     type: "metrics" }
  ];
};
```

---

#### Section 04 "System" — Technical Depth with Collapsibles

This section hosts **Layer 3 (Technical)** content. The architecture diagram is visible by default; deep-dives are collapsed:

```
04 SYSTEM
├── System diagram (visible)
├── Key flows (visible)
└── [Collapsible deep-dives]:
    ├── ▶ Architecture decisions [click to expand]
    ├── ▶ Code samples [click to expand]
    ├── ▶ Claude prompts used [click to expand]
    └── ▶ Data model [click to expand]
```

Designers scroll past. Engineers click in. Both paths are supported.

---

#### Section 05 "Use Cases" — Interactive Cards

This section benefits most from the sticky rail + interaction pattern:

```
05 USE CASES
├── Filter pills: "Admin" | "Customer" | "Ops" | "Web" | "Mobile"
├── Card grid (3-4 cards visible)
│   └── Each card: Quick summary + [Expand]
│       └── Expanded: Flow diagram, annotated screenshots, outcome chips
└── Outcome chips: "-35% handle time", "+20% conversion"
```

Clicking a use-case expands inline to show scenario → solution → outcome.

---

#### Mobile Section Navigation

Based on fin.ai pattern — horizontal scrollable pills:

```
[IMPACT] [01 Problem] [02 Constraints] [03 Approach] [04 System] ...
                        ← swipe →
```

Or: The hero with metrics IS the first view, then numbered sections scroll vertically below.

---

> [!warning] No Tabs — Scrollytelling Instead
> **Tabs hide content and break mobile UX.** They contradict progressive disclosure.
>
> **The scrollytelling approach**:
> - Single scrollable page with sticky navigation rail
> - IntersectionObserver for scroll-synced highlighting
> - Technical content collapsed by default (Section 04)
> - All content discoverable by scrolling
>
> This serves xAI's "technical first" reviewers who want depth within 1-2 clicks, AND design leads who want to skim-scan.

---

### Lab Section (Stage 5 Gate)

**Current PRD**: `/lab` for interactive experiments

**First-principles upgrade**: This is your TECHNICAL PROOF section. Not optional—but must avoid "gimmick" perception.

> [!warning] Demo Quality Bar
> Without strict framing, AI demos read as novelty ("cool but shallow"). Design leaders evaluating taste will penalize gimmicky demos. Every lab demo must pass this test:
>
> **Is this demo worth a design lead's time?**
> - [ ] Does it solve a real problem (not a toy)?
> - [ ] Does it show design thinking (not just code)?
> - [ ] Does it work reliably (no broken demos)?
> - [ ] Does it load fast (< 3 seconds)?
> - [ ] Would I show this in a portfolio presentation?
>
> If any answer is "no"—don't ship it. One polished demo > three half-baked ones.

**Why this matters specifically for you**:
- Anthropic Claude Code role: "HTML/CSS/JS prototyping" required
- All AI labs value builders over polishers
- Your differentiation is "designer who codes"
- BUT: Gimmicks hurt more than they help

**What to include (quality over quantity)**:
1. **Live interactive demos**: Components you've built, not just videos
2. **Source links**: GitHub repos, actual code
3. **Clear context**: What problem does this solve? Why did you build it?
4. **Speed markers**: "Built in X hours" (shows velocity, not toy status)

**Specific lab experiments to build**:
- An interactive component from one of your case studies (stakeholder dashboard widget?)—real utility, not demo-for-demo's sake
- A "how this portfolio was built" technical breakdown—valuable for Anthropic Claude Code role
- A Claude Code workflow visualization—but only if it genuinely shows insight, not just "look I used Claude"

---

### The Agent Page (Differentiator—With Caution)

**Current PRD**: `/agent` with AI chat interface

**First-principles upgrade**: This CAN be a differentiator, but only if it's genuinely useful—not gimmicky.

> [!warning] Gimmick Risk Assessment
> An AI chat that just says "I'm Ion's portfolio assistant!" is worse than no agent. Design leaders will see through novelty.
>
> **The test**: Would a recruiter or design lead actually USE this to learn about you faster than reading the page?
>
> If the answer is "maybe" or "no"—deprioritize the agent page. It's not required. It's only valuable if genuinely better than navigation.

**Why it COULD work**: Most designers don't have this. You can build it. It demonstrates:
1. You can actually build with AI (not just design for it)
2. You understand the Claude API
3. You're comfortable with AI-native workflows

**How to make it not gimmicky (or skip it)**:
- **Option A (useful agent)**: Train it on your actual case studies, make it genuinely faster than clicking around. "Which of Ion's projects involved compliance constraints?" should return a useful answer in 2 seconds.
- **Option B (proof of concept)**: Show the agent exists but don't push it as primary navigation. It's proof you can build, not a replacement for good UX.
- **Option C (skip for v1)**: Focus on case studies and lab. Add agent later if you have time. A missing agent is neutral; a bad agent is negative.

**If you keep it, show the work**:
- "View system prompt" option for technical visitors
- "View source" link to GitHub
- Clear framing: "This is a technical demo, not a novelty"

