## Part 12: Trust Artifacts Layer

Beyond case studies, you need "proof objects" that reduce trust risk:

### Evidence Ledger
A compact, scannable list of concrete proofs:
- PR links (merged code)
- Agent demo links (live systems)
- Decision log snapshots
- Metrics with dates

Can live as a sidebar section or dedicated page. Think of it as your "receipts."

### Decision Log Pattern
For each case study, include a compact decision log:

```
DECISION LOG: [Project Name]

┌─────────────┬──────────────────┬─────────────┬───────────────┐
│ Inputs      │ Options          │ Choice      │ Impact        │
├─────────────┼──────────────────┼─────────────┼───────────────┤
│ User research│ A: Full rebuild │ B: Iterative│ 40% faster    │
│ showed X    │ B: Iterative     │             │ delivery      │
├─────────────┼──────────────────┼─────────────┼───────────────┤
│ Compliance  │ A: Custom UI     │ A: Custom   │ Zero audit    │
│ required Y  │ B: Standard comp │             │ issues        │
└─────────────┴──────────────────┴─────────────┴───────────────┘
```

This is GOLD for design challenge rounds—shows how you think under constraints in 5 lines.

### Proof-of-Work PDF (AI-Generated to Avoid Staleness)
A single page recruiters can forward internally:
- Your photo + name + title
- 3 proof points (10+ years, AI agents, ships code)
- 3 project thumbnails with 1-line outcomes
- QR code to portfolio
- Contact info

**Why this matters**: Recruiters copy-paste to Slack. Give them something formatted to forward.

> [!warning] Staleness Risk
> Static PDFs and evidence ledgers go stale quickly. Stale evidence (outdated metrics, old project lists) undermines trust instead of building it.
>
> **Solution: AI-Generated PDF**
> Build a simple tool (or use the Agent) that:
> 1. Pulls your current case study data (titles, outcomes, metrics)
> 2. Generates a fresh PDF on demand
> 3. Timestamps it ("Generated January 2026")
>
> This could be:
> - A `/generate-pdf` button on your portfolio that hits an API
> - Part of your Agent: "Generate my proof-of-work PDF"
> - A simple script you run when needed
>
> **Bonus**: This IS the hero project territory—a useful AI tool that solves a real problem (keeping portfolio collateral fresh).

### Redacted Depth (With Safe Reveal Mechanism)
For sensitive Ledgy work:
- Show what you can publicly (anonymized, high-level)
- Add "Full version available on request" with clear path

> [!note] Safe Reveal Mechanism
> "Full version on request" fails when recruiters actually ask and you have no system. Options:
>
> 1. **Private deck link**: Password-protected PDF or Notion page with full details. Share password in interviews.
> 2. **NDA-gated reveal**: "Happy to share full details under mutual NDA during interview process."
> 3. **Live walkthrough**: "I walk through the full version in portfolio presentations."
>
> **Recommendation**: Create a private case study deck (PDF or Notion) for each sensitive project. Share link + password after recruiter screen or in portfolio presentation. This is a common pattern—interviewers expect it.

- Creates curiosity + respects NDA
- Gives you something concrete to offer when asked

---

## Part 13: UX Direction Vocabulary

Three distinct feels to consider for your portfolio's personality:

### Direction A: Lab + Ledger
- Precise, scientific, but warm
- Ledger-like grids with lab notes aesthetic
- Feels like a briefing room
- **Best for**: xAI (first-principles), technical reviewers

### Direction B: Operator Console
- Crisp monochrome, fast-scan blocks
- Evidence-first, minimal decoration
- Feels like a control panel
- **Best for**: Speed-oriented cultures (OpenAI, Ramp)

### Direction C: Field Notes
- Narrative, textured, artifact-driven
- Feel of a working notebook with proofs embedded
- More personal, shows thinking process
- **Best for**: Anthropic (reasoning), Block (stories)

**Recommendation**: Start with Operator Console as base, add Lab + Ledger elements for technical sections, Field Notes personality in case study narratives.

